{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_oliver_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060060A/1930091901/0194.xml":{"full_text":"\u25a0WASHINGTON FIRST\nIN NEW INSURANCE\nDistrict Records Show In\ncrease of 13 Per Cent\nDuring August.\nBY EDWARD C. STONE.\nWashington reached the top of the,\nladder in the amount of insurance writ- j\nten in August, showing a gain of 13\nper cent, and beating the record of i\n\u2022very other section of the United States.!\nFlorida reported a gain of 12 per cent, j\nMaine 9 per cent and California 3 per\ncent, while every other State in the\nUnion announced a lass in insurance\nwritten in August, compared with Au\ngust. 1929.\nFigures just completed at Hartford\nand forwarded to The Star today show\na los.' of 10 per cent for the country\nas a whole, the most pronounced fall\ning off in the insurance business of any\nmonth this year. Early in the year the\naverage for the country revealed a gain\noVer a year in spite of the stock mar\nket crash of last November.\nThe gains were maintained through\nApril In May the month\u2019s business\nshowed a slight decrease, which was\nalso felt in June and July. The August\ndecrease of 10 4 per cent was not in\nfluenced by any particular section.\nThe August figures for Maryland\nshowed a drop of 16 per cent in busi\nness. insurance business in Virginia fell\noff 6 per cent and West Virginia lost\n14 per cent. Arizona was at the bot\ntom of the list with a decline of 30\npier cent. Among the Southern States\nAlabama was off 17 pier cent. North\nCarolina 15, South Carolina 23, but\nGeorgia lost only 6 per cent.\nWhen the first eight months of the\nyear are considered ordinary life in\nsurance shows an increase. The volume\nof insurance sold in the first eight\nmonths of this year is larger by 1 per\ncent than the volume paid for in the\nsame period last year. The Pacific\nStates still continue to show the largest\ngain, but the West, North Central and\nMiddle and South Atlantic also show\na gain during this period. In contrast\nto only three States and the District\nof Columbia for the month of August,\nfor the eight-month period, 23 States\nare ahead of their 1929 volume and\n3 States just equal what they paid for\nin the first eight months of 1929.\nThe research bureau has figures for\nthe 12-month period which ended Au\ngust 31. 1930. This period shows a gain\nof 3 per cent over the preceding year.\nOnlv one section, the West South Cen\ntral\u2019, failed to equal its production in\nthe preceding 12 months.\nParris\u2019 Death Shocks Bankers.\nDeep regret is heard in the financial\ndistrict over the death of Albion K\nParris, a leading financier here ,for\nnearly 40 vears. While a co-founder of\nthe investing firm of Crane. Parris\nCo,, he had not been active for many\nyears, although he still had a desk in\nthe office and dropped into the office\nnearly every day when in the city. He\noften recalled the days when he took\na horse and buggy and drove about\nthe city delivering securities.\nMr. Parris helped to found the Wash\nington Stock Exchange back in 1881\nand was one of its most ardent sup\nporters. His history of the exchange is\nconsidered the most complete record\nof the membership, the securities listed\nand the methods of trading in the early\ndays ever prepared by any member.\nHe was an active trader on the ex\nchange in the good old days, when seats\nsold for SIO,OOO each. At one time he\ndid a great deal of writing about the\nmerits, or demerits, of Washington se\ncurities\nGenial, enthusiastic, a close student\nof finance, Mr. Parris had a host of\nfriends. He was one of Georgetown's\nmost loval residents and his passing\nwill be felt far outside the financial\ndistrict.\nBonds Lead Local Exchange.\nIn the final session of the weelt on\nthe Washington Stock Exchange the\nmost interest was manifested in bonds.\nWashington Gas 6s, series A, opened\nwith a SI,OOO sale at 103, followeo by six\nsmaller sales at the same figure. Wash\nington Railway t Electric 4s came out\non the board at 89Va and Barber Ross\n6\u2019is registered a SI,OOO sale 89.\nIn the stock division Capital Traction\nsold ex-dividend at 60 3 8 this being the\nfirst transaction since the August report\nwas out showing a gain in earnings un\nder the new street car fare schedule.\nPotomac Electric Power 5Vi per cent\npreferred moved at 108%, 15 snares of\nColumbia National Bank stock at 410\nand 10 shares of Merchants\u2019 Transfer\nStorage common changed hands at 103.\nPresident George O. Walson appointed\nEugene E. Thompson and Thomas W.\nBrahany of Crane, Parris Co., William\nB. Hibbs. dean of Washington brokers;\nCarroll Glover, a former president of the\nexchange, and Edward N. Hillyer, vice\npresident of the exchange and the\nUnion Trust Co. to represent the or\nganization at the funeral of the late\nAlbion K. Parris.\nGleaned in Financial District.\nGeorge E. Fleming, vice president of\nthe Union Trust Co., is motoring\nthrough New England on his vacation.\nHe is now in the vicinity of Portland,\nMe\nGeorge L. Starkey, president of the\nNational Bank of Washington, Is com\npleting a motor trip through the moun\ntains oi New Hampshire and New York.\nHe will be back at the bank Monday.\nOtis Olazebrook, a partner in the\nbrokerage firm of G. M. P. Murphy St\nCo, has been elected a director of the\nAmerican Hide Leather Co.\nThe New York Title Mortgage Co.,\nwhich recently opened a Washington\noffice, has declared the regular quar\nterly dividend of 50 cents per share,\npayable September 30 to stock of rec\nord September 19.\nThe Baltimore St Ohio Railroad has\ndeclared regular quarterly dividends of\n$1.75 on common and $1 on the pre- J\nfprred stock, both payable December 1 j\nto shareholders of record December 1. j\nJohn W. Poole, controller of the cur-\nrency, announces the voluntary liqui-\ndation of the Drovers St Mechanics\nNational Bank of Baltimore. The bank\nhas a capital of $1,000,000.\nNovember 1 is the date set for mak\ning the merger of the Federai-American\nand Merchants Bank Trust Co.,\neffective. This is 10 days after the\nstockholders of both banks pass on it.\nDULL TRADING LESSENS j\nINTEREST IN MARKET\nNEW YORK, September 19 (Special), j\n\u2014Discouraging dullness is doing more to j\nundermine the morale of security hold-\ners than any other single market factor, j\nincluding unfavorable dividend actions\nand poor earnings reports.\nBrisk buying of standard leaders at\nthis point is all that traders ask for as\na ignal to get in, but neither the pub\nlic nor the semi-public will show much\ninterest in the market as long as it is\nsolely a professional pair.\nARUNDEL CORP. DIVIDEND.\nBALTIMORE, September 19 (Spe\ncial).\u2014Arundel Corporation has de\nclared the regular quarterly dividend of\n75 cents, payable October 1 to stock of\nrecord September 23,\nArundel Corporation <sand and gravel\ncontracting business) reports for eight\nmonths ended August 31, 1930, net\nprofit of $1,730,154 after depreciation\nand taxes equivalent to $3.51 a share\non 492,556 no-par shares of stock. This\ncompares with $1,442,851, or $2.92 a\nshare in the corresponding eight months\nof 1929. August net profit was $222 811,\nagainst, $205,911 in August, a year ago\nCurrent assets on August 31 last,\nwere $5,846,287 and current liabilities,\n1419,487.\nFINANCIAL.\nI NEW YORK STOCK EXCHANGE I\nReceived by PrtvmU Wb\u00ab Direct to IV Mar Oflke*.\nNote\u2014All stocks a re sold In one hundred-share lets\nexceptling those designated by the letter s (80s) (tSOs)\nwhich shows those stocks to he sold In odd lets only.\n,-Prev 1930 Stock end Sales\u2014 Prev.\nHlsh. Low Dividend Rate. Add 00 Hlsh Low. Close. Close\n42'. 21 Abitlbt I\u2019ow A Paper 3 2iv. 21 21(4 22\n86\", 64% Abitlbi rAP pf (6). 1 75 75 75 75\n37*. 2D* Adams Exp (1. 60). 23 26*4 25% 26*4 26%\n34% 29*4 Addressosr\u2019ph (114). 1 *l% 3D* 3134 313*\n23'-. 8 Advance Rumley, 19 9 9 9V*\nIS 34 Ahumada Lead 1\n156*. 103'* Air Reduction 04 34 109 120\u2019* 1 173