0% 60% 50%\n66% 32% Mo Kan A Tsxas (2). 1* 40% 38% |B% $9%\n108% 92 Mo Kan A Tex pf (T) 1 97 97 K 97\n98% 67 Missouri Pacific 3 66% 66 66 66\n145% 115% Missouri Pac pf (6).. 5 120 r2O 120 120\n40 16% Mohawk Carpet 8 18% 18 18 19\n63*4 35 Monsanto Ch (gl M) 60\u2019% 60 40 42(4\n49% 29% Montgom Ward (I).. 249 36% 84% 34(4 35%\n16% B*4 Moon Motors 1 6 6 6 6\n2 1 Mother Lods (20e).. 2 1% 11% 1\n11% 3% Motor Meter GAEI.. 13% 3% 3% 3%\n81 34(4 Motor Products 2 41% 41% 41% 44%\n34 21 Motor Wheel (I) 13 22% 21 21 22%\n26% 12% Murray (B)(2% stk) 9 16% 16% 16% 16%\n58% 30% Nash Motors (4).. 4ft 34 32% 33% 34\n132 94% Nash Chat ASt L (6)110* 96 96 96 96%\n26% 10% Nat Acme (1%) 14 12% 11% 11% 18\n20 8 Nat Bella Hess 18% 8% 8% 9\n93 71 Nat Biscuit (t* 30 88% 82% 83 84%\n83% 41 Nat Cash Reg A (t 4) 42 46 44% 46 46%\n62 45(4 Nat Dairy <|2) I*l 68 52% 52% 53%\n24% 18% Nat Dept Stores (1). 1 14 14 14 14%\n189% 124% Nat Lead (tl) 1 128% 128% 128% 130\n1 119% 116 Nat Lead pf (B) (I). 60s 119% 119% 119% 118%\n68% 32 Nat Pow ALt (1)... 193 46(4 44% 46% 46%\ni 62% 51% NatStssl(J). 68% 58 68 54%\n124*4 100% Nat Supply (5) 1 104% 104% 104% 106*,\n116 106% Nat Supply pf (1)... 10a 111 111 111 110%\ni\ni (Continued on Pace 14.)\n\u20224*\nSHARP BEAR DRIVE\nDEPRESSESSTOCKS\nLeading Shares Are Beaten\nDown as Large Offer\nings Appear.\nBY CLAUDE A. JAGGER,\nAuoriktcd Frew Financial Bdltor.\nNEW YORK, September I#.\u2014The\nstock market broke below recent resist\nance levels today in active selling that\nwas stimulated by a rumor of political\ntroubles fn Germany. Seizing this re\nport, which quickly proved to be un\nfounded, as ammunition for their own\nguns, professional bears offered leading\nIssues in large blocks and succeeded in\nbringing out considerable liquidation\nfrom other sources. Volume increased\nsharply.\nDenial of the rumor concerning Ger\nmany arrested the break shortly after\nnoon, when losses of 3 to 5 points or\nmore had developed, but the market,\nafter making an irregular recovery,\nturned dull for a time and then went\ninto another decline, in which the\nearlier recessions were extended.\nUnited States Steel, dropping to 163,\nwas off 4 points, while American Can,\nJohns-Manvllle, Sears-Roebuck, Beth\nlehem Steel, Du Pont, United Aircraft\nand Eastman Kodak lost 3. Westing\nhouse Electric broke more than 6, J. I.\nCase dropped 7 and Worthington Pump\nand Allied Chemical about 8. American\nTelephone and General Electric yielded\na couple of points.\nThe weakness of the market found\nmany holders ready to part with their\nstocks. Some disappointment has been\nexpressed this week over the failure of\nthe anticipated business revival to mar\nterialize in a broad way and taiany who\nhad made purchases during the ad\nvances of late August and early Sep\ntember had placed stop loss orders\ni which were uncovered by the declines.\nThe day's reports from industry and\ntrade were rather nondescript, although\ni it. appeared that large copper producers\nhad definitely cut the domestic price\ni to cents a pound. The cus\ni tom smelters were also holding at that\nfigure.\nBaltimore Outlook Improves,\nBALTIMORE, September 19 UP).\u2014\nBradstreet\u2019s Baltimore district trade re\nport says:\n\"There is considerably less pessimism\nas an increasing number of mines re\nport slow but gradual improvement.\nEven industry is looking up Collections\nare in many instances better. To be\nsure, thus apparent upturn in business\nis in part seasonal, but many regard it\nas the dawn of the much looked for\nbusiness revival.\nWashington Ticker\nBY CHAS. P. SHAEFFER,\nAssociated Press Staff Writer.\nAn early conference will be held be\ntween officials of the Bureau of Inter\nnal Revenue and Treasury Department\nto discuss the advisability of publishing\nimmediately the new standard rate of\ndepreciation for all machinery, includ\ning farm implements, which will hence\nforth be used as a base in computation\nof taxes.\nThe new schedule, which constitutes\none of the most important tax studies,\naside from the actual rates themselves,\nhas been completed by the Revenue\nBureau and awaits only the perfunctory\napproval of Treasury officials. While\ninterested heads are reluctant to dis\ncuss the proposed new policy prior to\nofficial announcement, it is known the\nsponsors regard it as an almost perfect\nstructure, providing greatest benefits to\nboth taxpayers and to the Government,\nat the same time rendering the com\nputation of taxes an extremely simple\ntask.\nThe new structure has been the sub\nject of intermittent study over the last\nfive or six years. The finished sched\nule represents a compendium w\u2019hlch\ntakes into consideration rates effected\nthrough compromise, through the Board\nof Tax Appeals and through other\nagencies which sought to establish the\nfairness of the levy, thus representing\na chart that embodies every factor\ndeemed proper to be considered in de\npreciation charges, even in cases of the\nmoat complex caliber.\nThe present years depression bids\nfair to establish an unenviable high rec\nord for bank failures in this country.\nTms comes to light in the figures of sus\npensions for the year up to and includ\ning two weeks of September which\nshows a total of 835 failures.\nDeposit liabilities of the suspended\ninstitutions have not been brought up\nto date, but involved $210,881,000 up to\nand including the month of June. For\ncomparative purposes, the Federal Re\nserve Board reports total suspensions\nfor 1929 aggregated 642 institutions with\ndeposits of $235,000,000.\nAll these deposits, of course, will not i\nbe lost, as some of the banks will be en\nabled to reopen, while others will return\nsome percentage to depositors when\ntheir affairs are liquidated.\nOs this total of 635, 84 were members\nof the Federal Reserve System.\nA slight note of optimism is sounded\nby the monthly chart of failures, which\nshows a declining tendency. January\nwas the high month with 97 failures,\nfollowed in numerical order by April\nwith 95, February with 85 and March\nwith 75. In the months of June and\nAugust 87 failures occurred, while 65\nclosed their doors in July. For the first\ntwo weeks of September a total of 32\nstupended operations.\nThe steady climb of America's auto\nmobile industry to the top has not been\naccomplished without its full share of\nhazards.\nThe Automotive Division of the Com\nmerce Department states that 640 dif\nferent makes of passenger cars have\nbeen offered to the public in the 35 years\nsince the automobile was first intro\nduced, of which only 45 have survived\nto the present day.\nPrior to 1905 there were 186 types put\non the market of which 11 are still being\nmanufactured. The next five years saw\nthe advent of 129 new makes of which\nfive still exist. In the following decade\n187 new makes were Introduced of which\n11 are still being manufactured. In the\n10 years Just drawing to a close 77 new\nmakes have appeared of which 18 still\ncommand more or less favor.\nThe high spot in number of new\nmakes introduced occurred just after\nthe turn of the century. Forty-seven\nnew makes were put on the market in\n1901; 33 in 1902, and 51 in 1903, the\npeak year. In each of the following\nyears over a 20-year span at least 10\nnew makes were introduced.\nSilver stocks in Shanghai on Septem\nber 11 totaled 209,400,000 taels, of which\n126.000,000 taels were held in native\nbanks. The corresponding figures for\nSeptember 4 were 209,200,000 taels and\n125,000,000 taels, respectively.\nSyeee and silver bars were valued at\n109,100,000 taels on September 11, as\ncompared with 110,100,000 taels on Sep\ntember 4. The total number of silver\ndollars in Shanghai on September 11\nwas 100.300,000, as compared with 136,-\n200,000 on September 4.\nA French governmental decree pro\nmulgated September 12 increases the\nimport duty on com in the grain from\n10 to 24 francs per 100 kilos gross. This\nrate applies uniformly to all countries.\nThe powers of resistance displayed by\nprincipal German industries in weather\ning the severe depression which began\nabout a year ago are stressed in recent\nadvices to the Department of Com\nmerce.\nWhile industrial and trade activity\nduring the last month showed some\ni further average recession the decline is\nsaid to be no longer, general, but largely\nrepresenting the readjustment of indi\nvidual Industries to current market con\nditions.\nAs increasing clarity develops regard\ning governmental financial and trade\npolicies following the general elections\non September 14 another important\nelement of uncertainty now adversely\naffecting business may be eliminated,\nwith highly beneficial effect on the\npsychological angle, which plays an im\nportant role in the present depression.\nSome evidences of improvement in this\ndirection is already noted In more confi\ndent statements by business leaders.\nADVERTISING CALLED\nGUIDE TO BUSINESS\nExpert Holds Proper Promotion\nIs Aid to Trade\nProsperity.\nSpecial Dispatch to The Star.\nLOUISVILLE, Ky.. September 19\nThe greatest development of financial\nadvertising In the next 10 years will be\nto make it the authoritative guide of\nbusiness along the road to even and\ncontinuous prosperity, Earnest Elmo\nCalkins, nationally known leader of ad\nvertising thought, declared in a talk\nhere before the fifteenth annual con\nvention of the Financial Advertisers\u2019\nAssociation. Financial institutions can,\nif they will, Mr. Calkins said, become\nthe conservators of prosperity. They\nneed only use what they know and\nspread It by advertising to avoid such\nfinancial catastrophes as we had last\nFall and escape the consequences of\nthem w\u2019hen they occur. That, Mr. Calk\nins reiterates, is the new job for finan\ncial advertising.\nBank advertising and new business\npolicies must be co-ordinated with the\nbasic principles of sound management\nor the best advertising in the world will\ndo the bank no good, according to Her\nbert V. Prochnow of the advertising\nstaff of the First National Bank of Chi\ncago. In his talk. Mr. Prochnow said\nthat the future of all bank advertising\nIs inseparately lntermeshed with the\nscientific management of the institu\ntion. It is only when a bank turns new\nbusiness into profits that the results of\ngood advertising are realized, he stated.\nAdvertising and new business activities\nare geared up or geared down to the\nefficiency and the profits of the whole\nbank, he\nMoney to Loan\nMoored by Bri\u00bb deod of trust on real eetata.\nPrevailing Interest and eommteslon.\nJoseph 1. Weller \u2018jgfffo l> tST\nSpecializing in Real\nEstate Investments\nJAMES Y. PENNEBAKER\nNat. 5291 1520 K St. N.W.\nFIRST TRUST\nLOANS\nReatonablm Rat**\nCourtmoun Tr*atm*nt\nTHOS. E. JARRELL CO.\nREALTORS\n721 10th St. N.W. Nat'l 0765\nI REAL ESTATE LOANS\nMad* at Low Interoat Rates\nTYLER RUTHERFORD\nApnllratien* Invited on high\napartments and dwellings, and nartleo\n,rl on well located buaines* properties,\nfor 8. or I# year*. If \u00bbo desired.\n1520 K St. N.W. National 0475\nOffices\nSaul Building\n925 15th St. N.W.\nSeveral desirable rooms at\nvery reasonable rents. Inspec\ntion invited.\nB. F. SAUL CO.\nNat 2100 m 15th St N.W.\nf^omcES^\ni Hill Building C\n17th A Streets\nSeveral single offices and 4\n14 suites available at most rea- y\nj r sonable rentals. 4\nL Apply to Repronentotlve,\n4 Room SOO.\ni Moore Hill, Inc.\n730 17th St. N.W.\nmmmm iilHnaM\u00df\u00df\u00dffiKn\u00df\u00dfl\nPittsfield. Mass, fy\nA Standard Low Premium Policy\nfor\nBusiness and Professional Men\nDetail* on Request\nF. T. Koons, General Agent\nUnion Trust Bldg. Nat. 1015\n=====r===r\u00b1==s===s=s==sas\nLet Us Make Your\nFirst Mortgage\nLoan!\nLoans may be secured on de\nsirable, income-producing Wash\nington real estate at a minimum\ncost.\nA SAFE INVESTMENT\nwill be found in our real estate\nmortgage bonds!\nReal Estate\nMortgage Guaranty\nCORPORATItJIt\nCapitol Resources, 53,500,0